{"cursor":"6435","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Chinese| pic=Tu Di Gong.jpg|piccap=Tu Di Gong| |c=|p=TÇ DÃ¬ GÅng|poj=ThÃ³-tÄ«-kong/ThÃ³Í-tÄ«-\nkong|l=Earth God |c2=åå° or åå¬|p2=TÇ DÃ¬ or TÇ GÅng |c3=ç¦å¾·æ­£ç¥|p3=FÃºdÃ©\nZhÃ¨ngshÃ©n|l3=Earth god of wealth and merit |c4=å¤§ä¼¯å¬|p4=DÃ bÃ³ GÅng}}\n\n\n'Tu Di Gong' (also known as 'Tu Di', 'Tu Gong', 'Tudi Yeye' and 'Dabo Gong'), is\na Chinese earth god worshipped by Chinese folk religion worshippers and Taoists.\nA more formal name for Tu Di Gong is 'Fude Zhengshen' (ç¦å¾·æ­£ç¥), literally the \"God\nof Fortunes and Virtues\". The Encyclopedia of Malaysia, vol.\nReligions & Beliefs, edited by Prof. Dr M. Kamal Hassan & Dr. Ghazali bin Basri\nISBN 981-3018-51-8 [http://www.selectbooks.com.sg/getTitle.cfm?SBNum=28708\nwww.selectbooks.com.sg] Keith G. Stevens, Chinese Mythological Gods,\nOxford University Press, USA, (November 8, 2001), pages 60, 68, 70, ISBN 0-19-591990-\n4 or ISBN 978-0-19-591990-5\n\nIn China, every village had a shrine to Tu Di Gong. It was this deity who was in\ncharge of administering the affairs of a particular village. In traditional\ntimes, village concerns were primarily agricultural or weather-related. This god\nwas not all-powerful, but was a modest heavenly bureaucrat to whom individual\nvillagers could turn in times of drought or famine. \n\n, Taiwan.]]\n\nToday, he is still worshipped by many Chinese, with many housing small shrines\nwith his image, commonly located under the main altar, or below the house door.\nMany worships make prayers to him for wealth and their well being. He is also\ntraditionally worshipped before the burial of deceased persons to thank him for\nusing his land to return their bodies to the earth.\n\nCommoners often called Tu Di Gong \"Grandpa\" (yeye), which reflects his close\nrelationship to the common people.\n\nTu Di Gong is portrayed as an elderly man with a long white beard, a black or\ngold hat and a red or yellow robe, which signifies his position as a bureaucrat.\nHe carries a wooden staff in his right hand and a golden ingot on the left.\n","linknr":193,"url":"Earth_God","recorded":1375071550,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Tu_Di_Gong&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Tu_Di_Gong&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Tu_Di_Gong","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Earth_God&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Earth_Goddess","/wiki/Earth_goddess","/wiki/File:Tu_Di_Gong.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Tu_Di_Gong.jpg/220px-Tu_Di_Gong.jpg","/wiki/Chinese_language","//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%9C%9F","//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%9C%B0","//en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E5%85%AC","/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Min_Chinese","/wiki/Hokkien","/wiki/Pe%CC%8Dh-%C5%8De-j%C4%AB","/wiki/Chinese_language","/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Chinese_language","/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Chinese_language","/wiki/Mandarin_Chinese","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/File:HK_Shatin_%E5%A4%A7%E5%9C%8D%E6%9D%91_Tai_Wai_Village_land_god_Tu_Di_Gong.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5d/HK_Shatin_%E5%A4%A7%E5%9C%8D%E6%9D%91_Tai_Wai_Village_land_god_Tu_Di_Gong.JPG/220px-HK_Shatin_%E5%A4%A7%E